      "choices": [
        {
          "id": 16699,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Epitope, the specific part of the antigen recognized by an antibody</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 16700,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Paratope, the binding site on an antibody</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 16701,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Iditope, an individualized component of an antigen</span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 16702,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">Isotope, a variant of an antigen with different atomic mass</span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">A 30-year-old scientist is researching antibody-antigen interactions. She is particularly interested in the specific part of the antigen that is recognized and bound by an antibody. Which term best describes this specific site on an antigen?</span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q2482801",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 34996,
      "difficulty_level": "beginner",
      "subjects_id": [
        6
      ],
      "solution": "<p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Ans. A) Epitope, the specific part of the antigen recognized by an antibody.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option A:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Epitope </strong>or <strong>antigenic determinant is the smallest unit of antigenicity. </strong>It is defined as a <strong>small area present on the antigen comprising of few </strong>(four to five) <strong>amino acids </strong>or <strong>monosaccharide residues</strong>, that is <strong>capable of sensitizing T and B cells </strong>and <strong>reacting with specific site of T cell receptor or an antibody</strong>.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\">The <strong>specific site of an antibody that reacts with the corresponding epitope of an antigen is called paratope.</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/04/screenshot-2024-03-04-154742.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"500\" height=\"501\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Explanation:</u></strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option B</strong>. <strong>Paratope </strong>is the <strong>binding site on an antibody</strong>, not the antigen as is asked in the question.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option C</strong>. <strong>Iditope </strong>refers to a <strong>unique structure within an antibody</strong>, not an antigen.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Option D</strong>. <strong>Isotope </strong>is a term related to <strong>atomic physics </strong>and not relevant to antigen-antibody interactions.</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Educational Objective:</u></strong></span><span style=\"font-size:11pt;\">&nbsp;</span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Epitopes may be grouped into two types:</strong></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><ol><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Sequential or linear epitope</strong>:&nbsp; It presents as a <strong>single linear sequence of few amino acid residues</strong></span></li><li><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong>Conformational or non-sequential&nbsp; epitopes </strong>are found on the <strong>flexible region of complex antigens </strong>having tertiary structures. They are formed by bringing together the&nbsp; surface residues from different sites of the peptide chain during its folding into tertiary structure.</span></li></ol><p>&nbsp;</p><p><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><img src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2024/03/04/screenshot-2024-03-04-154759.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"700\" height=\"393\"></span></p><p>&nbsp;</p><p style=\"text-align:justify;\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt;\"><strong><u>Ref:&nbsp;</u>Apurba Sastryâ€™s Essentials of Med Microbiology 1st/p105, 2/e p111, Ananthanarayan 10/e p90</strong></span></p>",
